Exercises

  1. Plot California protected areas by access level and by layer
ggplot(data = cpad_super) +
  geom_sf(aes(color = access_typ, fill = access_typ)) +
  theme_bw()

ggplot(data = cpad_super) +
  geom_sf(aes(color = layer, fill = layer)) +
  theme_bw()

  1. Plot the Global human modification layer. Hint: just use plot for ease
plot(ghm)

  1. Crop and mask the raster to fit the area of the shapefile. Plot each step. Hint: just use plot for ease
ghm_cropped = crop(ghm, cpad_super)

plot(ghm_cropped)

ghm_masked = mask(ghm_cropped, cpad_super)

plot(ghm_masked)

  1. Extract the global human modification values at each California protected area.
cpad_ghm_values <- terra::extract(x = ghm_masked, y = cpad_super)
  1. Summarize the mean of human modification within each protected area
cpad_ghm_summary <- cpad_ghm_values %>%
  group_by(ID) %>%
  summarize(gHM_mean = mean(gHM))
  1. Join this summary with the protected area database. Plot these values.
cpad_ghm <- full_join(cpad_super, cpad_ghm_summary)
## Joining with `by = join_by(ID)`
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = cpad_ghm, aes(color = gHM_mean, fill = gHM_mean)) +
  theme_bw()

  1. Join the entire human modification layer to the protected area database. Remove geometry and any missing values.
cpad_values <- full_join(cpad_ghm_values, cpad_super) %>%
  select(-ID) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>% 
  drop_na()
## Joining with `by = join_by(ID)`
  1. Create two boxplots of human modification values, 1 across access_typ and 1 across layer. View these side by side.
p7 <- ggplot(data = cpad_values) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = access_typ, y = gHM)) +
  theme_bw() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    y = "Human Modification Index",
    x = "Access Level"
  )

p8 <- ggplot(data = cpad_values) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = layer, y = gHM), outlier.shape = NA) +
  theme_bw() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    y = "Human Modification Index",
    x = "Agency Type"
  )

p7 + p8
